## Recommended: `System.IO.Abstractions` NuGet package

This is the established solution for making `File.*` and `Directory.*` calls testable — no need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public void SaveData(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public string LoadData(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
// Directory.Exists will return true for "/data"
var service = new MyService(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.LoadData("/data/config.json"));

service.SaveData("/data/out.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/out.txt"));
```

**Key points:**
- Only replace call sites that you need to test — no need to wrap every `File`/`Directory` member.
- `IFileSystem` is stateless, so register as `AddSingleton`.
- `MockFileSystem` provides an in-memory filesystem with full path/directory semantics — no temp files needed in tests.
